<br>
You're a cop.  You see some guy pull a gun on your partner and point it as his head.  You shoot him.  It turns out the gun wasn't loaded and the guy was just goofing around and meant no harm to the officer he pulled the gun on.<br>
<br>
Whose fault is it that the guy got shot and killed? It's his own damn fault.  Based on the information that you had at the time, it was entirely reasonable and logical to assume that the the guy holding the unloaded gun wanted to kill your partner and would do so if you didn't kill him first.<br>
<br>
Sure the gun wasn't loaded, sure the guy was an innocent civilian.  Sure he had no malicious intents.  However, he was an idiot to pull an unloaded gun on a cop and he paid the price for his extremely poor judgment with his life.<br>
<br>
Of course it would be better if he didn't die, as it would have been better if these people in the van didn't die (assuming that they actually were innocent).  However, if you are stupid enough and take certain actions, you bring it upon yourself and bear full responsibility for it.<br>
<br>
This is all of course ignoring the possibility that they actually did intend to kill US soldiers by turning a vehicle into a weapon.  We won't ever know if that was their intent or not, but it doesn't matter.  The US soldiers did the right thing.<br>
<br>
In the above analogy, what would you have done, wait for the guy to pull the trigger to see if the gun was loaded?  If you would have, you're an idiot, and certainly not someone I'd want to have for my partner.<br>
<br>
